AGI - Clamorous fur in a large warehouse in Tokyo where a cup of 24 carat gold tea, worth more than 10 million yen, about 61 thousand euros, was taken away in the middle of the day. To make a fuss about the fact that the precious object, put on sale during an event of the luxury warehouse of the Takashimaya chain, was in a window that had not been locked. The Japanese media reported that footage of the security cameras in the warehouse showed a man putting the cup in his bag and then drifting undisturbed, as if nothing were.
&nbsp;
"This is one of the most expensive items in the collection consisting mainly of tableware and tableware displayed in the store, all over a thousand pieces," said a spokesman of Takashimaya. "It was kept in a transparent box that was not locked at that time, so that it could be easily extracted and examined closely by customers," he specified the same source. The collection on display in the store will remain open to the public visit, but the leaders of the chain ensured that, in the light of the incident, safety measures will be strengthened.
&nbsp;
The police are still looking for the alleged guilty. This excellent theft further marks public opinion after another incident that last December involved the same chain, just under Christmas: over 800 Christmas cakes, delivered to customers, were damaged, once they arrived at home and removed from the package. The obvious flaw had aroused an avalanche of criticism on social media and Takashimaya's direction had been forced to make a solemn public 'mea culpa' in a television press conference held by Kazuhisa Yokoyama, the managing director. Takashimaya, the Japanese response to Harrods, said he had "translated the expectations of many" and assumed responsibility and bowed it deeply, during the press conference, as a sign of remorse.

